The term “drama,” outside of the theatrical or literary sense, can often replace the “controversy,” but for situations that do not result in severe legal repercussions; “drama” is typically, but not limited to, a person-to-person ordeal that is glorified by a set group of people. Drama can range from two A-List celebrities arguing about the implications of a joke to an unnecessary fight between two close friends in a rural public school, but in both cases, a set group of people must be aware of this dilemma for it to be considered “drama” rather than personal bickering. People’s reactions to drama could be aggressive and mean towards the unfavorable party or completely unreactive, and a considerable influence on how people react to the drama is how their preferred side in the debacle appeals to the audience of the drama. The correlation between the reactions of both the participants and the audience is direct; the audience is likely to react as if moved by the same emotions portrayed by their preferred participant. Nevertheless, common patterns in people’s reactions to drama can be discovered when examining a selection of people based on set criteria; such criteria could be income, ethnicity, age, etc. However, one intriguing pattern for reactions to drama is found when examining people under the criteria of biological sex. More specifically, there seems to be a tendency that males are less likely to start drama with another male, and less likely to be an active audience member in male-to-male drama, compared to the exact opposite situation involving female-to-female drama. This is not to say that female groups are encouraged to be involved in drama, but that some sociological concepts suggest that male groups are prone to develop a collective consciousness that handles conflicting situations in a way that avoids drama from occurring.
Now, the initial thought for this claim arose from my firsthand experiences in being involved in or discussing all types of drama, whether it is with friends, family, or the public. These observations are solely based on my personal interactions with males in high school to college, so, clearly, I cannot justify my argument around conclusions based on these observations. However, it is important to discuss why these claims came to be a rational conclusion for me because that could lead to discovering what underlying principles are affecting these scenarios. 
So, reflecting on interactions of my own, I discovered that males tend to only start drama when there is a solid and justifiable reason, male drama climaxes marginally quicker than female drama, most males prefer to be a neutral spectator in all dramas, and males are more likely to resolve drama in a confrontational (sometimes violent) way than females. To start detailing my experiences, I will explain a common scenario that occurs with both sexes that could lead to drama: someone talks badly about another person. Surprisingly, a simple or rude critique often sparks conflict between people. However, even though both sexes are subject to rude words, my experience makes me believe that males usually do not create drama for minor personal attacks, while their female counterparts are more likely to start a drama from a similar level of personal attack. Most male dramas I experienced were instigated by issues that personally affected a male negatively (such as snitching to authority that results in disciplinary action) or issues that portray a male in a false light in a serious situation (attack on someone’s personality that could hurt them socially).
 Nevertheless, if a male drama sparked from a minor personal attack, my experiences would argue that the drama would not stay relevant more for than a week usually; but if a female drama arose from a similar circumstance, the drama is likely to stay relevant for months. I would say that males dislike making a big deal about their drama in most cases, so they will attempt to calm the situation by being apathetic. But if a male chose not to be apathetic and instead was actively encouraging a drama to an audience for a minor personal attack, I would argue that most males would choose to just not be involved, unless they were close friends with someone involved in the drama. Still, if males get involved in a supportive role, the drama would usually be resolved quickly compared to female dramas. This is because male drama has the tendency to be resolved with direct confrontation, whether it is verbal or violent, and soon after the drama will become irrelevant. Regardless, this information does not explain why these trends are noticeable to an observer.
In a study from 2006 by psychology professor Brett Stoudt titled “You’re Either In or You’re Out,” students at an all-male high school, Rockport, were studied and interviewed for the purpose of detailing the collective mindset and sociological trends of the students given the setting. The study found that Rockport experiences more student violence than co-ed public schools because of the strong encouragement of a hegemonic masculine mentality built within the school’s educational and social systems. 
Hegemonic masculinity is a concept that describes a dominant form of masculinity that all males should strive to reach in terms of masculine norms. The concept is often reinforced by the functions of society, functions which are supported by censorship and peer discipline of others for not conforming to the norms; social functions that encouraged hegemonic masculinity were seen actively within the school. For the school, hegemonic masculinity was encouraged through the curriculum and academic competitiveness (functions), which led to strong criticisms from peers and sometimes exclusion from friend groups. This mentality can actively be noticed in the school’s sports program, where teammates often bully each other for faults, such as being a first-year student or not starting on the team. These conflicts would often be violent, lending a cause-and-effect explanation for why the school’s violence is more common. Even still, these conflicts would be handled in abrupt manners and the victims understood the reasoning for the conflict and accepted the violence because that is the norm; those who followed the norms would be considered “in” the hegemonic masculine mentality, and those not following norms were considered “out.” The study even suggests that hegemonic masculinity is good for the students since it builds a sense of self and sets a standard to follow if they seek a privileged status. Still, this concept is present outside of this specific example found within the study.
Hegemonic masculinity can still be found in lots of portions of modern culture and can provide background for how males deal with drama. Like Rockport, my own high school had aspects of competitiveness and peer discipline that encouraged this concept. While not to the same level as Rockport, my high school (and likely all public high schools) builds hegemonic masculinity as a norm. However, I would argue that, even in the cases of Rockport, violence, bullying, and competitiveness found within a public school do not often result in drama. In fact, I would argue that hegemonic masculinity attempts censor drama through peer discipline and violence at any level. Causing drama would be seen as unnecessary and not ideal when a conflict is justified by this shared belief. This concept provides the sociological reasoning for why males tend to be involved in less drama than females.
In summary, male dramas occur less frequently than female dramas. This statement is proven through the sociological concept of hegemonic masculinity, which discourages male drama and reinforces the concept through violence. Although these ideas have focused on high school students, it does seem likely that hegemonic masculinity is prevalent in popular culture due to the number of institutions that support the concept and, comparatively, less popular male dramas occurring than female dramas. Furthermore, a debate about how males deal with drama versus females dealing with drama and mental health is often questioned. Do males deal with drama in a healthier and more just manner than females? Should hegemonic masculinity be encouraged if the benefits are significant?

When we think of power, the first thing we think of normally is not class level. In the United States we tend to avoid phrases that identify different levels of classes as it is seen as disrespectful. Even though people do not like using these terms, when it comes to dealing with strictly wealthy people, they use it as a symbol of power. The more money they have the more powerful they are among others in their class. In my experience at institutions such as public schools, class is also a touchy subject.

While a parent may see one child that is in a lower class as someone that is not going to succeed or get into a major university, another parent will see a child from a wealthier family and assume that that child is automatically going to get what they want in life. How Television and Social Media Re-Define What It Means to Be Beautiful

Rebecca Walker
Department of Sociology, University of North Carolina Wilmington
Sociology 105-002
Professor Christopher S. Elliott
April 28th, 2021










	
In today’s society, body image has become a very sensitive topic. Instead of bringing women together, it has driven them farther and farther apart.  Growing up, girls often don’t think about how their body looks compared to others until they start puberty.  With everyone experiencing puberty at different times and speeds, it can cause girls to develop insecurities with their bodies.  As they are exposed to television, they see many different body types and start to compare themselves to them.  This holds true for teenagers and adult women as well because once they outgrow Disney Channel and Nickelodeon, they are exposed to channels and shows that depict the female body in its rawest from.  As they see this, they also see adult men who seem to only be attracted to women with slimmer and curvier figures.  This holds true with pornography as well because the most popular adult actresses are the skinnier women with “perfect” vaginas.  This causes small flaws to stick out even more in a woman’s mind. They start questioning their own beauty and whether or not they amount to anything compared to these perfect models.  Naturally, everyone wants to fit in, no one wants to be considered ugly or unattractive by society, but by making the beauty standards so specific it makes it hard to really embrace body positivity. Everywhere you go, you are more likely to see the skinny and “perfect” women, but do you ever stop to question how they got that way?   A lot of celebrities including Taylor Swift, Lana Condor, Kesha, Paula Abdul, Demi Lovato, Candance Bure, and many others have struggled with different kinds of eating disorders.  They have told their stories and it has allowed others to tell their stories as well in order to bring awareness to how important it is to love yourself and be who you are without feeling the need to change. 
	Sociologist Charles Cooley believes that individuals develop their self-image by observing how they are perceived by the other people around them.  Cooley has referred to this concept as “the looking-glass self” and in today’s society, it is affected even more by the implications of television and social media.  As women in particular start to determine their self-worth, it becomes heavily reliant on how people around them see them compared to how they see others.  As they take into account what they see around them, they use it as a mirror to measure their value in relation to others.  While some people are able to see themselves for who they truly are, for others it’s like looking through a fun house mirror.  All of their flaws are distorted to the extremes and they start hating themselves for it. 
	Perceptions of what is considered attractive varies across different cultural groups especially for the female body size and shape.  Based on the way our brains encode bodies and faces, just by altering what adults are exposed to, you can manipulate their attraction preferences.  Historically in European art, the depictions of the female body shape remained the same throughout the classical and medieval area but switched to preferring a curvier body type during the modern era due to shape-altering undergarments (Boothroyd et al. 2020).  To what extent are the perceptions of the female body really affected by television consumption?  An article from the Journal of Personality and Social Psychology titled “Television Consumption Drives Perceptions of Female Body Attractiveness in a Population Undergoing Technological Transition”, really puts things into perspective.  The authors conducted their research and experiments in a remote region of Nicaragua by sampling from villages who had different levels of access to television.  Their studies concluded that participants in the low television access villages showed a stronger preference for larger body types than those in the high television access villages.  It was also discovered that the control samples that were taken from the capital, Managua, preferred the thinnest body types of all of the recorded samples.  This data alone shows how much television and media consumption can re-define beauty in a group of people.
	How does this new definition of beauty affect women?  Every woman’s body is different than another’s.  While the new beauty standards may be in favor of some women, it is also not in favor of others. As stated in an article titled, “Risk Factors That Predict Future Onset of Each DSM-5 Eating Disorder: Predictive Specificity in High-Risk Adolescent Females”, from the Journal of Abnormal Psychology, women’s pursuit of the thin beauty ideal can result in body dissatisfaction/dysmorphia, and this causes some women to start binge eating and participating in other unhealthy weight control behaviors that could lead to anorexia or bulimia (Stice, Gau, Rohde, & Shaw 2017).  These eating disorders affect 13% of females and even create a higher risk for future obesity, depression, suicide, and substance abuse. If a woman has one eating disorder, she is at an extremely high risk to develop another, they literally stack up and continue to get worse.  These are the demons that some women end up dealing for their entire lives. The sad part is, a lot of them don’t even recognize that they need help, they are living their lives thinking what they are doing is natural and necessary. A good example of this would be YouTube star Eugenia Cooney.  She has been posting on her channel since 2013, she has severe anorexia and almost looks she’s skin and bones.  She never really opened up about her disorder and she’s posted regular videos. People often accused her of promoting her lifestyle but in recent news’s she has stated that she has been struggling for a long time and is working on getting help as she enters her late 20’s.  Instead of attacking women, we should be doing everything we can to help them realize that they need help, it took way too long but she’s in rehab and getting the help she needs. There are still people suffering in their homes away from society dealing with this as well. They don’t see people all the time that can encourage them to be better. If they care enough all they have is social media. So in order to save the people we can’t even see we need to work together to help create a better more inclusive body positive content for those who don’t feel as represented.
	Despite how it may seem, some advancements have been made in the right direction on social media.  Body-positive posts on social media aim to challenge mainstream beauty ideals and encourage the acceptance and love of all female body types.  How much has it really been able to do? An article titled, “#BoPo on Instagram: An experimental investigation of the effects of viewing body positive content on young women's mood and body image”, from the Journal of New Media and Society aimed to investigate the effect of viewing body-positive social media posts.  One hundred ninety five young women, ages eighteen to thirty years old were randomly chosen to view either body-positive, thin-ideal, or appearance-neutral social media posts.  The results showed that brief the women who were exposed to body positive posts exhibited an overall positive mood, body satisfaction and body appreciation, relative to thin-ideal and appearance-neutral posts.  With that being said, both thin-ideal and body-positive posts were associated with increased self-objectification (Cohen, Fardouly, Newton-John, & Slater 2019).  The women who were exposed to the skinny models, began reflecting on themselves and comparing themselves to the models, thus resulting in in dissatisfaction with their own bodies.  Like Boothroyd discusses in her article about eating disorders, this negative image can lead to the development of increased self-objectification, body dissatisfaction, and disordered eating behaviors in women.  However, with social media being filled with user-generated content, it allows for bodies that don’t exactly fit into the beauty standards to finally have a voice and be seen by the public.  With this in mind, it allows for body-positive content to become really popular.  As of April 28th, 2021 on Instagram #bodypositivity has 7.5 million posts compared to the 1.8 million reported in June of 2018 by the authors of this article.  That growth that has been made over the course of 3 years is honestly amazing.  In order to improve body appreciation researchers have stated that it is extremely important to provide women with broader conceptualizations of beauty and to encourage women to surround themselves with social networks that encourage women to appreciate their own body (Cohen, Fardouly, Newton-John, & Slater 2019).  In the present study, women have been captioning their #bodypositivity posts with statements like ‘I am beautiful’, ‘I am beautiful despite my flaws’, ‘I am beautiful on the inside and out’.  These statements are a clear indication of the women actually adopting a broader sense of beauty to incorporate a variety of appearances and attributes.  These women are looking at the other women around them and instead of hating themselves, they are looking at it from a new view, a new view that speaks the truth, every body is beautiful, even your own. 
	Body image isn’t something that’s just a problem among women, men go through their own struggles as well, it’s just usually not on the surface.  While women are liked regardless of height, if a man is shorter than a woman, she usually won’t give him a second look.  There are always exceptions, but this is something that’s extremely common and shouldn’t be overlooked.  Other than height, men have just as many things as women to be insecure about.  So, while we are preaching #bodypositivity make sure everyone is included. Charles Cooley’s looking glass self can really be viewed at in many different ways.  A person’s self-online is going to be different based on the website that they are on.  A person’s profile on LinkedIn is going to present them in a completely different way than their Instagram or Twitter might present them.  Despite this persona being purely online, it still translates to the real world, they can never escape possible judgement and criticism.  As a person develops what is considered their cyber self, they are more likely to embellish when talking about themselves and some people even go to the extent of editing photos before they post them in order to remove any visible flaws.  In the world of social media, everything is represented by a number, your follower count and your like count being the most prominent.  People are going to like your posts more if you post more of what is considered “normal” and appealing. As the like count goes up, so can a person’s confidence.  If it goes too far a person can literally fall in too deep and end up dedicating their entire life to increasing follower and like count.  Say someone does put their all into it, and still continues to lose followers.  This causes some issues with body image that can only be saved through time and a group effort.  Social media is moving in the right direction by not censoring and shadow banning body positive content.  With the growth that has been made over the past few years we are definitely on the right track to embracing all body types into societies definition of beautiful.
	With all of the body positive content circulating, young women will be exposed to all body types instead of just what is deemed “perfect” by society.  With tv shows and models becoming more inclusive, it allows for better role models for our youth.  Hopefully this can reduce the number of young women suffering with eating disorders and depression.  With a wider variety of content being shown on television even adults can start to see beauty for what it really is.  Naya Rivera has a really beautiful quote that addresses this topic extremely well, “Butterflies can’t see their wings.  They can’t see how beautiful they are, but everyone else can.  People are like that”.  We need to continue to lift each other up and radiate positive energy to the people around us.  You never know what a person is going through behind the scenes, so do your best to treat everyone how you wish to be treated.  Everyone has their own demons to overcome and when you’re constantly surrounded by mirrors that show you those demons, it’s hard to do something about it.

The Conception of Self and Online Interactions

In The Self, the I and the Me, Mead argues that the conception of self is highly dependent on the setting that you are in. A setting that has become more popular in today’s society is social media. Additionally, Erving Goffman believes online interactions are frequently toxic because people are not invested. In order to create a more positive online environment, society should focus more on the importance of this setting.
One of Mead’s main points is that the self is experienced out of internal dialogue called the “I” and the “me.” In experiences the “I” comes first and is the immediate reaction to a stimulus. The “me” is next and is the objective evaluation of the previous reaction. Going back to Goffman’s point about online interactions, it is possible that the reason for these hostile interactions is due to the lack of “me” in the situation. In online activities people are more likely to act faster and therefore not go through the “me.” This avoidance means that the persons initial reaction with any evaluation is what comes out into social media. This process is due to the fact that these interactions lack investment on both sides.
The conception of self is changes based on the setting you are in. In online or social media interactions there is larger likelihood for a negative exchange with others. This is due to the absence of the “me” within the internal dialogue. With more investment in these online exchanges, it is possible to create a more positive online network in society.

Essay #6- Class in America 

	The class system in the United States is basically split up into three groups, the lower class, middle class, and the upper class. The lower class is characterized by those who are in poverty or below the official poverty line in the US. The middle class is commonly referred to as those who live comfortably and have opportunities that allow them to advance. The final and most influential class is the upper class, which can be split further into sections like the power elite. These classes have been around as long as the US itself but the inequality that was seen is only growing between the three different classes. The class systems are growing further apart from each other with each passing year but not much has been done to try and stop it. 
	The readings describe a very divided class system that the US has produced over a couple hundred years, the lower class is left with no opportunities to try and advance in class while the middle class lives comfortably in its professional class system, and finally the upper-class controls about one third of the whole countries wealth. In Gregory Montsois 2006 work, Class in America, he debunks several myths that the American public has accepted as truth, for example, he debunks that in the US every citizen has equal opportunity to succeed. Montsois goes on to explain that the evidence shows that the class inequality is growing which can be seen when analyzing income levels from the three classes. While I was growing up in an all-white household, we never really discussed those in poverty and those who are the “power elite” (as Domhoff describes them), but my siblings and I did understand that our family was middle class and living comfortably with a few hardships that would affect us. The collective conscious that was created in my household was one that did not focus on racial inequalities or class inequalities but that led me to not fully understand those issues until I was much older. The class system that was established by my collective conscious was one that thought people always lived comfortably and didn’t have anything to overly worry about which is not was Domhoff describes in his work, Power in America, he brings to light something that I never knew about growing up, the “power elite.” The power elite that Domhoff describes is people who have direct influence in our government via different methods such as lobbying. This class system that was in these readings was very different from what my collective conscious knew already. 
	The system in the us that establishes the lower, middle, and upper classes is one that is very intricate and usually misunderstood because of the collective conscious. The mainstream media removed class issues from their broadcasts leading people to not think they were an issue, but now we can see that it is a growing issue that has resurfaced and needs fixing. The inequality between the US economic classes is something that is ongoing and is in urgent need of addressing.

The label “upper class” describes the small percentage of Americans who control the most wealth in the country. According to USA Today, the top 1% of the population controls 25-30% of the country's wealth. Due to this immense wealth, families in the upper class are subject to more opportunities and privileges, further increasing the wealth gap in the country.
	The famous phrase, “the American dream” describes that with hard work and dedication, one can achieve immense success, no matter the social class they are birthed from. However, the truth often diverges from this belief. With the existence of the upper class, systematic inequalities have formed in America, making it extremely difficult for those in the lower classes to keep up. 
	One primary example of these inequalities is the schooling system. It is a proven fact that private schools are more effective for students than the average public school. However, due to the high cost of most private schools, more upper-class families can afford the tuition than lower-class families. The same goes for higher education institutions such as colleges. As college tuitions continue to rise, it has become much more difficult for middle to lower-class citizens to send their children to these universities. 
Along with inequalities in the schooling system, the job market is also unequal for those in the middle and lower classes. If one is unable to pay for better education such as private schools or college, they are automatically behind those students whose family provides them with these opportunities. This leads to many upper-class citizens getting higher-paying jobs based on the family and class they are born into. Once obtaining a higher-paying job than someone with less education or opportunities, this cycle of social class repeats for the next generation.
There are millions of real-world examples of this cycle around the country. A child born into a rich political family will almost always be more successful than the son of a janitor. A student who goes to a private school, on average, will have higher test scores than a public school student. The student with higher test scores will almost always get into better colleges, and therefore be hired for better jobs than the student who began in the public school system. These are just broad generalizations and examples of the social class cycle in America working for wealthy families and against the less wealthy.
The people in these upper-class families are not to blame for these harsh realities, but they can push to make a difference. People of the upper class have much more authority than people of the middle or lower class. The upper class often consists of politicians, business owners, and entrepreneurs who can sway the public. These distinguished people can promote reform to the class system in America and help those less fortunate than themselves. One primary way I believe people of lower classes can be helped is by decreasing the costs of education across the country. All levels of education should be more affordable for each citizen no matter the class they are born into. Making education affordable will help create equal opportunities and give children of lower classes the opportunities needed to attend college and meet the requirements of many high-paying jobs. One more reform method that could help specifically those in the lower class is addressing the housing crisis in our country right now. Housing costs are at an all-time high, and rising each day. This makes it much harder for even middle-class families to afford a house along with essential goods and services needed to survive. Ways of improving the housing market could be to change the methods used to build houses or abolish rules for homeownership in certain areas across the country. These are just two examples of ideas the government and the upper class can push for to improve the lives of the citizens in the classes below them.
Overall, the social classes and large wage gap in America is a prominent and growing problem that needs to be addressed. Addressing these problems will take members of the upper class to speak out and promote change across the country. Those born into the lower class should not be predetermined for less success than a child born into the upper class. We must re-attain the ideals of the American dream and make our country the land of opportunity once more.

Mental Health in the Military
	As far as mental health goes in the military, they want the members to talk about it, but they also punish them for utilizing the available resources.  Why would they continue to think that people would want to utilize their resources if they will inevitably be punished for it?  This goes to say that many service members participate in the front stage and back stage concept of how they present themselves.  It is used as a way to protect their careers from the harm that mental health institutions inflict.  And how the concept of “the looking glass self” has an immense impact on the actions of those serving.
	Many service members, especially on active duty, experience some form of mental illness, such as anxiety to depression and everything in between.  Most will deal with it in the comfort of their own homes and not seek professional help, because they know about the repercussions of utilizing the help.  This causes a lot of members to turn to a really dark place that is hard to get people out of.  If that happens, it is crucial to help them, or the worst of things could occur.
	The back stage element that they participate in is trying to cope with their mental health without professional help.  This does not work for everybody, but most will try it in the beginning.  A lot of unhealthy coping mechanisms that many participate in include drinking, drug abuse, self-harm, and many more.  There are also some healthy coping mechanisms such as working out and hobbies.  Most tend to participate in both, which puts the impression that they are doing fine.  People will say things like “Oh he’s been working out, so he must be doing okay.”  Which is exactly what the person wants the public to think.  
	The backstage is where all of the hard things tend to boil over and cause bad things to happen, but as long as they put on a good face at work then they are fine, according to higher-ups.  The front stage is what gets all of the glory in the military.  If they can put on a good face and do their job well, then they are good to go in the eyes of the military.  But if they have a slip up, the impression starts to do a 360.  That is when the back stage starts to merge with the front.  
	This causes problems within the service member’s career.  If one is to go to the mental health clinic, for even one visit, they can not deploy or go TDY, which is going to another stateside base for work.  And that causes a lot of issues, because most of people’s problems are on their home station and they would like to get away on occasion.  Not to mention, if the problems include money, then they are losing out on a lot from a deployment.  This also goes on for six months after the last appointment with the clinic, so it is not a little bump in the road.  It takes a long time for the restriction to fall off of their record.
	The front stage and back stage also applies to the mental health clinic.  They put on this face of wanting to help and provide for active-duty members, but when an individual actually gets into the room, they do not help as much as they should.  Which I know from personal experience.  The therapist that I had pretty much said I was cured, because I had not had a panic attack in a couple of weeks.  Clearly that was not the case.  They can go on and say it is because they are understaffed and have too many patients, but they should be able to at least act like they care when someone is back in the room with them.  
	The mental health problem also contributes to the concept of “the looking glass self”.  It is believed by many that if an individual is seeking help for mental health, then they are weak or not fit for duty.  Whether or not people actually think this of those that seek help is not the point in this situation.  The members will still think that this is how they will be viewed and it deters them from utilizing the resources available.  Active-duty members also do not want to scare off any potential friends or lovers with the notion of their mental health issues.
	Not everybody will run from a person that clearly voices their issues, but that is not the case for all individuals.  Some people just simply do not want to deal with the uncertainty or emotions in a person or do not know how to in some situations.  On the other hand, some people can not always be to blame, they just simply have not been around enough people with mental health issues, so they have no idea on what to say or how to respond.  Either way, this causes the members to not want to voice their problems, so they keep it locked away in themselves.  
	The “looking glass self” concept has a lot to do with the collective consciousness of society as a whole.  If there was not a huge negative stigma around mental health, then everybody would feel comfortable about talking about it.  But since there is that negative feeling surrounding it, most will hide the fact that they have problems or not associate with somebody that does.  The collective consciousness around mental health is a negative one, but with all of the new conversations being brought up, it is turning into a more positive tone.  
	Hopefully at some point the mental health epidemic will no longer be a huge problem for many active-duty members.  That they will change the policy of the six-month restriction, in most cases, so that the members will actually seek help with the available resources.  Making it so that the back stage and front stage of the active-duty members will not be as divided and unhealthy and the “looking glass self” will be seen in a more positive light.  
Until then, the conversations still need to be had and the higher-ups in workplaces need to step up their game and actually get to know their subordinates.  That will ensure that they will actually notice when somebody is not acting themselves, so they can intervene before it is too late.  Because once it is too late, the whole base will be under a lockdown.  Nobody will want to talk about their issues, because they do not want it to be a big deal that is broadcasted to everybody in the workplace.  Not to mention the hardships that it will put the family and friends of the individual through.
Making the talk about mental health more common and comfortable will cause many more to open up about their problems.  It will end the negative notation in most societies and, hopefully, lower the suicide rates among active-duty individuals.  Continuing to provide resources will also help with the climbing rate of mental health diagnoses and help to control them, so nobody feels left out of the conversation.

The Representation of Women in STEM Fields
	Science, engineering, technology, and math come together to create the acronym STEM which encompasses professions in all four areas. Historically, men have dominated these four areas of expertise while women have taken a back seat with fewer numbers enrolled in STEM courses and even fewer succeeding in the completion of said courses to continue onto a STEM profession. Even though the number of women in STEM fields has grown through the years these women still face barriers that make it harder to become leaders in their fields. If or when women make it into STEM professions, they face distortions in their representation in the media which makes it harder for their work to be seen without a feminine facade blocking its true value. Gender bias is only one aspect that these women face throughout all levels of their education. Women have been wrongfully represented in a field that they worked very hard to get into, though this is the case, women across the globe have begun to band together to change the face of STEM to be a more inclusive group of professionals. 
	The media is an entity that holds much power in today’s society. Media outlets include newspapers, television networks, radio, social media, and many more. These media outlets can choose what and how to represent anything they want, for example, some news networks are more liberal and tend to cover negative events that involve conservative legislation. Several studies have been conducted to assess how the media portrays women in STEM, one, Mwenya Chimba and Jenny Kitzinger’s Bimbo or boffin? Women in science: an analysis of the representations and how female scientists negotiate cultural contradictions. During this study they looked at 12 prominent UK newspapers over a six-month period. They compiled a total of 7,903 articles about STEM with 51 of them being about specific scientists. When the researchers were assessing the representation within each article they looked at, “any reference to their relationship status, children, nationality, ethnic identity, and appearance.” They found that 16% of scientists that were mentioned were women with the other 84% being men. The findings suggested that women were more likely to have their age, relationship status, appearance, and parenthood mentioned somewhere in their description. This prompted an investigation into how women were presented in the description, specifically their physical characteristics, clothing, hairstyles, etc. The researchers found that many of the authors of these pieces focused on the scientists’ femininity with many physical descriptions. Some were described as “this petite, feisty communicator” and even “this 55-year-old academic’s mane of blonde hair” while the men that were written about had descriptions based on the “old scientists” such as Darwin or Einstein. This research shows that women were sexualized by the media despite their involvement in a very professional field. (Chimba, Kitzinger) The sexualization of women is just one way that women are misrepresented by the media in their STEM fields. 
	The struggles that women endure does not start when they enter their fields, but instead it starts with their education, specifically starting at the high school level. Women are less likely to be enrolled in Advanced Placement courses compared to their male classmates. The factor that affects this is gender bias because women are generally not persuaded to enter STEM professions as much as men are. (Robnett) Rachael D. Robnett conducted a study entitled, Gender Bias in STEM fields: Variations in Prevalence and Links to STEM Self Concept. Robnett mentions the “STEM self-concept” many times in her work and she describes it as, “the extent to which individuals believe they are capable of excelling in STEM fields.” It is important to note this when reading Robnett’s findings that the STEM self-concept is greatly affected by gender bias. The results of this study found that 61% of women experienced gender bias “at least once in the past year.” (Robnett) The overwhelming majority described the type of bias they experienced as, “feeling as though you had to work harder than male students to be taken seriously” and even “hearing negative comments about girls’ and women’s STEM abilities.” (Robnett) Robnett then correlated the amount of gender bias experienced to the lessening of the STEM self-concept in women actively attaining education in STEM. After reviewing her results, Robnett addresses what can be done to lessen gender bias in STEM and even just trying to lessen the effects of the bias. One way that is described in her research is educating faculty and students of STEM classes on how to create a more inclusive environment to attract anyone to the field. Although the existence of gender bias varies based on the level of education and field in which they are studying, the existence in general is the problem that impacts women the most. (Robnett) Gender bias greatly impacts the STEM self-concept and self-esteem of these women that have courageously decided to enter these fields. 
	The media representations of women in STEM accompanied by gender bias in the field makes for a difficult existence for women involved in the field. The struggles that women face are not new developments in society, these have been going on since the beginning of time. One early example of men thinking less of women was when Aristotle said, “We should regard women’s nature as suffering from natural defectiveness.” This shows that women have been inferior to men for hundreds of years. In Simone de Beauvoir’s work Women as Other he states that, “He is the Subject; he is the Absolute, She is the Other.” This idea of “women as other” is exactly what women in STEM are facing in today’s world. They are seen at the “other” in STEM fields because of the long history of them being male dominated. The connections between Aristotle and Beauvoir’s writings shows that women have been seen as inferior to men for much longer than society thinks. When they are sexualized by the media it is just a current way to classify them as the other. When gender bias is introduced, it is generally accepted by society because of the long history of pushing women out of leadership roles because they are the others of society.
	Though women have experienced struggles in STEM fields there has been a recent push for people to support the entrance of women into fields that a normally male dominated. Social media has made this a global movement to advance the presence of women in these male dominated professions. Reem Alkhammash conducted a study titled, It Is Time to Operate Like a Woman’: A Corpus Based Study of the Representation of Women in STEM Fields in Social Media. This study focuses on the emergence of “hashtag activism and digital feminism” that has taken the world by storm in recent years. Alkhammash describes the gender imbalance in STEM as a “leaky pipeline” and that means that women usually begin in STEM fields but then leak out and choose to not continue in the profession. She goes on to explain that women are disadvantaged by institutional and cultural factors in STEM, these factors are, the lack of female preparedness for STEM careers, poor female attitudes towards STEM since their childhood, and the absence of role models for women to follow and look up to. This is what sparked her research into digital activism to see how the world was turning the page on cultural norms and pushing for more female representation in these highly professional fields. Alkhammash’s research began with the acquisition of tweets from the social media platform, Twitter. She compiled tweets such as, “#womenintech, #GirlsWhoCode, #womenTechTalk, #womeninSTEM, #womenInSTEM, #womeninscience, #momscancode, and #ILookLikeASurgeon” (Alkhammash) In total, Alkhammash collected 14,611 tweets that ranged from October 31, 2017 to November 1, 2017 with most of the tweets coming from Portland, Oregon, US and Los Angeles, California, US. This immense number of tweets shows that the United States is leading in the digital activism that calls for more women to enter STEM as a profession. The digital activism is greatly helping women enter STEM fields and retain their careers for life. Another writing that supports the claim that women are entering STEM fields is Wendy M. William’s editorial, Underrepresentation of Women in Science: International and Cross Disciplinary Evidence and Debate. In her work she states that the number women that have transitioned to pursuing PhDs has been on the rise in recent years which means researchers and policy makers need to abandon the “leaky pipe” metaphor for the cause of women leaving STEM fields. She found that these new ideas included “campus childcare centers” instead of further enforcing gender quotas for hiring more women. Alkhammash and William’s writing shows that women have progressively been entering STEM, but they still have a long way to go. 
	The fields of science, technology, engineering, and math or STEM as it is commonly known is a field that is predominantly male with a smaller number of females. This lack of women in these fields is caused by a multitude of factors including the lack of informative media coverage as opposed to coverage that focuses on their private life and gender bias that these women experience throughout their STEM education. Mwenya Chimba and Jenny Kitzinger explained that women are usually sexualized in their media coverage instead of being focused on because of their research or subject area. This unfair representation in the media is a contributing factor to the lack of women in the fields in question. Not only are they unfairly portrayed in the media, but they face bias based solely on their gender and never on their cognitive skill level. This gender bias that women face in STEM fields was researched by Rachael D. Robnett and she found that the increase in bias faced by women significantly decreases their chances of continuing in STEM education, which is unfair to them. Based on these struggles that women face getting into STEM, the world has responded by focusing a spotlight on recruiting and supporting women in STEM through social media and digital activism. This hashtag activism has inspired many women to pursue careers in STEM despite their struggles. Women in STEM is one the rise and is on its way to become a more equally represented profession.

The ‘looking glass self’ is the concept that we view ourselves based on how we believe that others are seeing us. We are continuously thinking about how we are perceived, and if we decide that someone has a bad perception of us then we choose to adopt those negative thoughts. But why do we care so deeply about how other people view us? It is part of our innate desire to be a part of something. The theory of the collective consciousness correlates to our perception of ourselves being directly tied to the opinions of the people around us. 
	These concepts compliment one another in the sense that the collective consciousness provides an explanation for the looking glass self. The looking glass self as a theory cannot be entirely explained without a reason as to why people care. Why people are so concerned over how they appear, why it is ingrained in humans to go along with the status quo. The collective consciousness answers these questions, people want to be liked and appear a certain way because everyone desires to be a part of something. People want to be accepted by society and have a sense of purpose within a larger group. Being a part of the collective consciousness provides the individual with security and meaning, this set of beliefs and traditions is essential to any society. These shared values bring people together and are the glue for a functioning society, people need things that can unite them. 
	One aspect of the looking glass self that the collective consciousness does not directly explain is how people take on how they believe they are being perceived. Cooley says that the individual will believe about themselves however they think someone else believes about them. That people value their peers’ opinions so much that if they have the inkling that someone does not like them, they will internalize those ideas and think about themselves negatively. This is a step further than simply valuing how you come across to the outside world. This means that the experience of the self is created only by interaction, meaning that we do not experience the self on our own. That who we are is formulated from how we want to be regarded and then how we believe to be regarded. The collective consciousness provides the spaces for the individual to experience the self. Without groups such as religion, schools, sports, etc. people would not have the opportunity to experience the self through interaction. Because we place such high importance on these groups, this is where people take into account how they are being received and judged. 
	To summarize my analysis, the collective consciousness and theory of the looking glass self go hand in hand when understanding each concept. The looking glass self shows the individual how they experience themselves and how other people play a key role in that. While the collective consciousness demonstrates why other people are such an integral part of understanding who we are and how we act.

In the Unite­d States, different groups of pe­ople have power and mone­y. This impacts how society works. Class and power are ve­ry important parts of the social system. They de­cide how resources and chance­s are shared. They also show who has advantage­s and disadvantages. This piece looks at how class and powe­r connect. It explains how they shape­ American life. From how wealth and status are­ divided, to the ways power works in place­s like schools and jobs, looking at class and power gives insights into the­ American experie­nce. By studying the past, prese­nt, and future, we can understand the­ forces behind socio-economic influe­nce in America's society and politics.

What is socio-economic influence?

Money and powe­r  shape how people live­. Some groups have more of the­se than others. This lets the­m make rules and call shots. They can ge­t resources and jobs. Their life­ chances are bette­r than those with less money and powe­r. Groups with less money and power have­ fewer choices. The­ir voices are not heard as much. Whe­re you stand in life depe­nds on your social class. Someone's social class is based on the­ir income, education, and job. Classes with more­ money and power are at the­ top. Classes with less money and powe­r are at the bottom. There­ is an uneven spread of we­alth, status, and chances in society. Social class makes the difference. Those occupying higher social classes often wield greater economic resources and social capital, affording them increased opportunities for advancement and influence. Concurrently, power, both institutionalized and informal, serves as a mechanism through which socio-economic influence is exercised, enabling certain individuals or groups to assert control over economic resources, political institutions, and cultural narratives (Domhoff, 2013). Whether through corporate lobbying, media ownership, or elite networks, the pe­ople with money and power ofte­n have big advantages. They ge­t more opportunities that add to their we­alth and status. Meanwhile, others with le­ss money and power struggle. Unde­rstanding this pattern requires looking at how mone­y and power impact society. We must se­e how class divides link to systems that privile­ge certain groups over othe­rs.

Dynamics

The dynamics of socio-economic influence are multifaceted and complex, reflecting the interplay of various factors that shape individuals' and groups' access to resources, opportunities, and power within a society. At its core, socio-economic influence encompasses a web of interconnected relationships, institutions, and processes that determine the distribution of wealth, status, and influence. One key aspect of this dynamic is social stratification, which refers to the hierarchical arrangement of individuals and groups based on factors such as wealth, occupation, education, and social status (Macionis & Plummer, 2012). This stratification system creates distinct social classes, each with its own set of privileges, opportunities, and constraints. Moreover, socio-economic influence is often reinforced and perpetuated through mechanisms of power and privilege, which enable certain individuals or groups to exert disproportionate control over economic resources, political institutions, and cultural narratives (Domhoff, 2013). This can manifest in various forms, including corporate lobbying, media ownership, and elite networks, all of which serve to amplify the influence of the economic elite while marginalizing disadvantaged groups (Gilens & Page, 2014). 

How society can be positively, or negatively affected

The exploration of "Class and Power in America: Exploring Dynamics of Socio-Economic Influence" holds the potential for both positive and negative impacts on society. On one hand, a thorough examination of socio-economic dynamics can empower individuals and communities by fostering awareness of systemic inequalities and informing efforts to address them. By highlighting the interplay between class, power, and privilege, this exploration may catalyze social movements, policy reforms, and grassroots initiatives aimed at promoting equity and social justice. However, if not approached with care, such an exploration could also perpetuate harmful narratives or reinforce existing power structures, further marginalizing vulnerable populations and hindering efforts towards societal progress. Therefore, it is essential to engage in this exploration with a commitment to inclusivity, empathy, and critical inquiry, ensuring that the insights gained contribute to positive societal transformation.

Conclusion

In conclusion, the dynamics of socio-economic influence constitute a multifaceted tapestry woven from the intricate interplay of social stratification, power dynamics, and patterns of social mobility. Social stratification, manifested through various hierarchies based on factors such as income, education, and occupation, lays the groundwork for unequal access to resources and opportunities. Concurrently, power dynamics, whether institutionalized or informal, shape the distribution of influence and control over economic, political, and cultural domains. Furthermore, patterns of social mobility, influenced by factors like intergenerational wealth transmission and structural barriers to advancement, dictate the extent to which individuals can transcend their socio-economic circumstances.

The Ideas of The Collective Conscious and Religion 
	Emile Durkheim defined the term “The Collective Conscious” as the conditions of a subject within a society, and how said individual views themselves in society. This collective consciousness creates a shared group of ideas, beliefs, and collective knowledge in a society. The collective conscious defines almost all things in a society, whether correct or incorrect. For example, the ancient Egyptians once believed that each day, the sun god Ra would pull the Sun on his chariot each day, and would circle into the underworld at night, and come back in the morning pulling the sun. Back then, this was the truth of their society. They fully believed that a God would pull the sun because that’s what the collective conscious believed. Now we know that the Sun simply circles the Earth and doesn’t disappear into the underworld each night. However, this shows the power the collective conscious has over a society. It dictates the daily lives and beliefs of the society. The collective conscious also dictates what is good and bad in a society. An example of this was back in ancient times, same sex couples were much more excepted, such as in ancient Greece. Then for a period of time when Christianity was the reigning religion, it was deemed a sin and was extremely frowned upon. However now in recent times, same sex couples have been more accepted and embraced. The collective consciousness imprints on everyone in a society, dictating what morals people have and ultimately dictating what is right and wrong in society. While the collective conscious dictates a society, it also binds the society together. By believing in the same things, the group of people is brought closer together, and safety is found in a group that believes the same thing. This is how societies are formed. By a group of people coming together, having the same beliefs and ideas, solidarity is formed and a society forms. Now with this many things can affect the collective conscious and can influence and change it. For example, religion has a large affect on a collective conscious. Religious leaders have the power to influence the collective consciousness greatly. Especially during medieval time, the pope or other priests could simply change what they want and call it God’s will. By doing so they changed the ideas that many believed in and were able to change the collective conscious. Back to how the acceptance of same sex couples has changed over time, this is also a good example of how the collective conscious changes overtime with the views of the people. Overall, the collective conscious can change at a whim with everyday events and change with the views of the people. Specifically in recent years the collective conscious changes almost every year. With events that happen and just everyday fads and beliefs, the collective conscious changes. An important part of the collective conscious is also that the collective conscious must exist in a society, or a society cannot form. Without everyone agreeing and believing the same, then conflict would erupt in our society. We are starting to see this in our society as the population grows. More and more beliefs and values are starting to appear within our society, causing some conflict between groups to see which side will overpower the other and become the dominant collective consciousness. Happy Meals
We live in a fast paced society focused around convenience and what will reap the most benefits for us. Most Americans eat fast food one to three times a week. In a world where healthy, organic food is readily available in most places, why do we choose to eat unhealthy and unsatisfying meals? This is due to McDonaldization, which is this formula that has been created to turn the highest profit for the business and rope in the most consumers. However, this concept is not entirely unfamiliar to our society. Rationalization laid the groundwork for McDonaldization to take form, McDonaldization took Rationalization from only the workplace to nearly every aspect of our lives.
McDonaldization is based on four main attributes; efficiency, calculability, predictability and control. McDonald’s has drastically reduced the time that it takes for a customer to order and eat a meal. Mechanisms like drive-thru windows and order ahead apps cut down on time and employee exertion. They have also been successful due to the predictability of the meal, a Big Mac is the same in New York as it is in California. Corporate giants such as Walmart and Amazon have followed suit in the “McDonald’s way of doing things”. The business has a large amount of control as well. In fast food restaurants you are expected to know what you want to eat when you get to the window as well as have your money ready to pay. This pressure and control is put on the consumer so that they may have the most efficient work flow. 
Rationalization laid the groundwork for McDonaldization. Both theories are focused on the benefits of the corporation. Rationalization seeks to give the employer the highest profit and eliminate choice for the consumer. Both theories eliminate creativity and the human process of work as an expression. Instead work’s only purpose is to create what is most profitable rather than what the worker desires. In essence, these ideas reflect a quantity over quality mindset. Pre-Industrial Revolution the goods that were produced were handmade, took longer to create, and were influenced by the creator’s desire. The main difference between the two ideas is that Rationalization revolves only around the workplace. McDonaldization has worked its way into all aspects of our life, especially the social space. 
As mentioned before, there are multiple large corporations that have adopted the McDonaldization business model. We are so surrounded by convenience that as a group we perhaps don’t even realize the structures put in place for efficiency. Amazon is a great example of this, you can order anything you want at the click of a button. They have even gone so far as to remember your card information and shipping address so that all you have to press is buy, without a second thought. As well as with their various devices such as Alexa, all you have to do is tell Alexa to order you the desired item. The practices and results of these theories have vastly increased as our society has progressed, it is natural to expect them to continue to rise and nearly eradicate the concept of “small businesses”. It has been proven that when given the choice, most people opt for the bigger corporation that provides them with the easiest access to the desired product rather than seeking out a small business who takes longer but creates a higher quality product or experience. 
McDonaldization has revolutionized the way we experience our day to day lives and this would not have been possible without the movement of Rationalization during the Industrial Revolution. It can be debated if McDonaldization has more positive or negative outcomes in terms of the way individuals shop, eat, and interact with each other. It could be argued that McDonaldization has reaped far more benefits for the large institutions rather than the market.  These theories have certainly ushered in the era of convenience and created a large reliance on technology to make our lives easier. The implementation of Rationalization and McDonaldization are undeniably prevalent in our everyday routines and have forever altered what the public expects from big businesses.

Why do men feel pressured to haze or be hazed as means of validation of their identity? Throughout various communities and groups across society, particularly pertaining to those associated with masculinity, hazing has served as a means of inclusivity and acceptance, causing men to feel forced to accept means of humiliation and degradation in order to feel a sense of accomplishment and meaning within a group. In addition, older members of such groups arguably feel the need to haze as a means of securing their masculine roles as tough, strong, and dominant leaders, thus engaging younger members through the process. Although many have begun to combat and resist the idea of hazing, the same ideas and principles associated with hazing can still regardless be found and applied throughout masculine culture, thus suggesting a deeper cause. Overall, despite efforts being made to better understand and eliminate hazing, the base of the problem lies within the forced view from society on masculinity, holding that men should be expected to play the dominant role of being tough, strong, and emotionless in order to fit in. 
Due to the fact that men are expected throughout society to play the role of being tough, strong, dominant, and emotionless, this further causes them to fall subject to this flawed norm of society, with abuse and humiliation through hazing serving as validation. In order to combat these situations of abuse and humiliation as a means of validation, it is crucial to understand and oppose the norms brought on by hegemonic masculinity implicitly pressured through society.
One example in which this can be applied includes my experience in our varsity boys' soccer team in high school. Over the course of my time on the team, we would frequently play a series of games and activities we referred to as “consequences.” The idea of the game was to force whoever lost to perform a specific punishment or “consequence.” The activity was originally created as a “team bonding activity;” however the activity soon grew into a means of hazing and humiliation, particularly from the upperclassman. Over the years, the consequences created and forced onto the losers, typically lowerclassmen, became more and more outrageous, unbearable, and disgusting, mainly serving as a means of entertainment and a feeling of power for the seniors, who always conducted the activities. However, regardless of the punishment, members of the soccer team would almost always face up to the humiliation and degradation of the various consequences in order to feel viewed with validation. In contrast, members who did not face up to the consequences would frequently be regarded as “weak,” “scared,” or “unmanly,” while also frequently being harassed and targeted in future engagements of the activity. Additionally, players would also encourage you after completing a consequence, saying things like, “you’re the man, I can’t believe you did that, that took guts,” further conditioning you into thinking of yourself with a false sense of validation and “manhood.” On a soccer team built upon the foundation of brotherhood, love, and serving others, this situation of hazing acted as the total opposite, further negatively reflecting on the values and ideologies of masculinity. In order to avoid feeling viewed differently from other members of the team, as well as to feel a sense of accomplishment and validation among other members, players would give into this toxic ideology of not being “weak,” while instead being “courageous” and “strong” to further feel accepted.
An additional example from my experience that can be applied includes the idea of hazing within fraternities. In contrast to sororities, which usually contain almost no hazing, fraternities across the nation commonly use situations of hazing towards their pledges, ranging from mild to extreme instances. Common examples include forcing pledges to drive brothers to and from various locations, performing a specific set of chores, and wearing often absurd or specific outfits, with more extreme examples including performing a set of pranks, as well as the forced consumption of various narcotics. Fraternities often haze as a means for their pledges to prove that they are “man enough” to do whatever it takes to become a brother of the fraternity, while also weeding out those who are unsuccessful when performing these specific tasks. I have also noticed a large difference relating to the personality of some of my friends before and after completing their pledge process. Specifically, many of them seemed to be conditioned through hazing to express a style of masculinity built upon the foundation of acting “strong, tough, competitive, and emotionless” to not appear as an outcast. For example, one of my friends whom I have known since high school previously used to be much more energetic, lively, and full of emotion before he decided to pledge his current fraternity. However, over the course of the process, he gradually began to develop a more careless attitude, often hiding his emotions and developing a new sense of self in order to fit in better as a man within his fraternity. This ideology found within hazing not only causes pledges to feel a sense of rejection if not accepted, but further conditions the idea that in order to find a sense of meaning, purpose, and masculinity, one must be willing to not act as “weak” and instead be “courageous” through often demoralizing and degrading activities.
The concept describing that men hold stereotypical roles of being dominant, strong, courageous, aggressive, invulnerable to threats and problems, and emotionless relates to the idea of hegemonic masculinity. Brett G. Stroudt describes this idea when analyzing a private, mostly white, boy's boarding school named Rockport. According to Stroud, the school essentially served as a “breeding ground” for hegemonic masculinity, as the roles found within the ideology were frequently reinforced through each other, mostly due to their privilege as white males. The roles reinforced further taught the boys to hide their emotions publicly and instead share them in private with women. He further states that the reinforced roles also create a dichotomy between privacy and emotions as being related to women and needing to be kept out of a public, objective, rational classroom, further suppressing and lowering the standards of women (stroudt). Overall, when society begins to accept this ideology, this can become problematic as it thus assigns a stronger more powerful role towards men, while also assigning a lower, limiting role towards women.
I believe that situations of hazing, as described through my high school soccer team as well as within college fraternities, serve as excellent examples that can be explained through hegemonic masculinity. Essentially, allowing oneself to haze or be hazed in order to feel a sense of accomplishment and validation is built upon the foundation of the stereotypical roles described through hegemonic masculinity, such as toughness, emotionlessness, and courage. For example, over the course of our soccer team playing “consequences,” members who lost essentially agreed to engage in the humiliating punishments as this strengthened their sense of masculinity and validation among themselves and other players, while also avoiding the reputation of being viewed as “weak” and “cowardly.” Additionally, fraternity pledges also feel led to give into hazing as this will allow them to feel “strong” and “courageous,” while also becoming a part of a group that will help them find meaning among others who potentially view them with these roles. Oftentimes, leaders of groups like these, because of the dominant roles they play, believe it is important to express their role through hazing in order to be viewed by themselves and others as “strong, fearless, and emotionless” leaders, further contributing to the spread of hegemonic masculinity.
Groups such as fraternities and athletic teams also allow and encourage the reinforcement of these specific hegemonic masculine traits, as members within these communities are surrounded by others who believe the same way and are never challenged on their beliefs. Fraternities, for example, typically are very exclusive, picking and choosing exactly who they believe will serve as an asset within that group. Fraternities would not choose someone who they believed would act out against the hazing process or damage their reputation. Thus, within a selected group of mostly privileged men from similar backgrounds, these hegemonic traits are able to spread and reinforce easily. In relation to the soccer team, however, the process of hegemonic masculine reinforcement is slightly different. Although members are not specifically chosen due to these traits, oftentimes male athletes regardless still express similar hegemonic masculine traits, and when selected onto a team surrounded by others who share the same traits, these values are thus reinforced and encouraged. This ultimately leads to situations of hazing becoming more common, as members thus feel safe within their communities to practice it without repercussions. 
In sum, members within these selected, often privileged, communities typically allow themselves to haze or be hazed as this helps to build a sense of validation of their masculine traits to themselves as well as additional members. However, many members within these communities are unaware that in an effort to pursue this sense of validation, these traits are implicitly built off the flawed foundation of stereotypical hegemonic masculine roles. I personally have found evidence of this through examples including our “consequences” activity on my high school soccer team, as well as through witnessing college fraternity pledges endure humiliation in order to feel validated. Overall, how can one stop the reinforcement of hegemonic masculinity through means of hazing? One crucial tactic includes helping to spread awareness of the topic of hegemonic masculinity, further leading others to resist the support of its toxic traits, which are often applied and encouraged through means of hazing. In relation to groups such as fraternities and athletic teams, I believe it is possible to embrace a healthier definition as well as healthier values associated with masculinity, particularly those apart from hazing. This ultimately allows groups such as these the ability to lead one to find a more plausible and respectable sense of self, meaning, and validation.
