Estranged Labor in Modern Society
There is a collective consciousness surrounding the expectation to attend college after completing high school. This should make you think, was I given a choice of a different path other than college? Why did I decide to attend college instead of a trade school? Did I choose my career based on my own passions and interests? Or instead on the salary I would receive? These questions may show that you like many others followed a path that was expected. To attend school, college, and then start a career that you should stay in until retirement. 
	Relating to this is a journal titled, “Estranged Learning” by Jean Lave and Ray McDermott. The authors describe Marx’s writing as a “delivered phenomenon (McDermott and Lave 2006).” They believe that his idea of estranged labor has the power to make readers realize the relation between labor and profit. Furthermore, it is stated, “in critiquing the theories of political economy available in 1844, young Marx unwittingly wrote a quite devastating critique of the theories of learning available in 2002 (McDermott and Lave 2006).” Thus, showing that Marx’s idea of estranged labor that was based on a pre modern society still fits todays now modern society.
The journal goes on to use Marx’s work “Estranged Labor” as a template for what the authors are calling Estranged Learning. The new creation changes the concepts of Marx’s writing to focus on the education system and theory. For example, Marx’s original words are, “Political economy starts with the fact of private property, but it does not explain it to us (McDermott and Lave 2006).” To focus on education this is rewritten to say, “The educational establish starts with the fact of standardized knowledge, but it does not get explained to us (McDermott and Lave 2006).” The education system in our pre modern society is allowing and continuing the existence of estranged labor. The authors put this in very simple terms “labor produces commodities, learning produces commodities, labor produces the laborer as a commodity, learning produces the learner as a commodity (McDermott and Lave 2006).” Once again showing that the collective consciousness surrounding education is cause of estranged labor practices.
	There is also relation to Mark Andrejevic’s writing titled “Estranged Free Labor.” Andrejevic talks about the online economy.  He states that “the online economy relies upon consumers’ willing submission to increasingly detailed and comprehensive forms of monitoring (Andrejevic 2013).” All of this is due to the growth of online culture. The writing also then talks about the privacy issues that are created due to the everyday use of technology. The relation to estranged labor has to do with the fact that you do not receive a wage from online activity, however a wage is generated for others by it. The example Andrejevic gives is custom advertising, that is bought and sold to companies. He refers to a Wall Street Journal investigation and report that surrounds data mining. According to this study companies can pay $1 per thousand movie lovers. The economy relies on the buying and selling of this information to generate sales. This also increases the value of social media platforms.
	This use of the online economy creates a form of estranged labor. Consumers of social media and online sites are turned into a commodity that can be bought and sold. This is purely the idea of estranged labor that is given to us by Karl Marx. The difference is, these sales and transactions often happen without the acknowledge of the consumer. 
	Another relationship between modern society and estranged labor can be seen in a journal titled “Estranged Labor, Habitus, and Verstehen in the Rise of Extreme Endurance Sports” by Colleen P. Eren. According to this journal the number as well as participants of extreme endurance sporting events has grown rapidly since the 1970s. Examples of extreme endurance sports are triathlons, marathons, Iron-mans, and military-style obstacle courses. These events have millions of participants as well as spectators. Eren points out that previous studies have been done to analyze this growing phenomenon but not have analyzed it “from a microsociological perspective, looking at individual characteristics of participants (Eren 2017).” It is these characteristics that allow Eren to associate these sporting events with Marx’s idea of estranged labor. 
	Eren goes on to describe the participants of these events. She describes the number of amateurs involved to be extraordinary. A specific example of this is the increase of marathon participation in the United states from 1976 to 2013. In 1976 there was 25,000 participants and then 2013 there is a dramatic increase to 541,000 participants. Eren also points out that there is an unequal class distribution of those participating in extreme endurance sports. She is compelled by the number of participants that “have at least a bachelor’s degree, occupying well-compensated white-collar and professional jobs (Eren 2017).” An example given is that in 2016 at the Rock and Roll Marathon series the average income of a runner was $112,000 with 79% having at least a bachelor’s degree. 
	Eren also reports that in the 20th century there was a workforce trend away from high activity and manual labor. Instead, there was an increase in white collar and service industry workers. Eren claims that the growth in immaterial labor has an influence on extreme endurance sports. She is able to theorize this due to Marx’s idea of estranged labor. Due to estranged labor the worker is not involved in the process of making the product. This often takes away a person’s creativeness, activity, and interaction with others. The person then makes up what they are lacking in their job by participating in an extreme endurance sport. Eren also argues that there is lack of physical energy used in today’s labor, psychically for middle- and upper-class professionals. Therefore, extreme endurance activities are used to increase physical involvement. 
	Extreme endurance activities allow participants to feel less confined by the collective consciousness of estranged labor. As stated before, due to estranged labor, passions are often put aside in order to receive the best salary. The participation in these events allow the individual to find passion about something else. The increase of stationary jobs is also due to estranged labor in this modern society. These events are used to increase physical movement as well as bring purpose to the individual that may not have at their job. Participants in these events get to have moment of not working towards a profit that benefits someone else but instead have feeling authentic profit for themselves. 
	Karl Marx coined the term estranged labor in 1844 based off a pre modern society in Europe. However, this term can still be used to describe the modern society of the United. States. Due to a collective consciousness surrounding college and careers estranged labor is continuing to happen. Evidence of this can be seen in our own education system, as shown by McDermott and Lave in “Estranged Learning.” Estranged labor is also produced by the online economy. Consumers of social media are being bought and sold as commodities in order for these companies to make a profit. This can be seen by Andrejevic’s work titled “Estranged Free Labor.” Lastly, a result of estranged labor is shown by Eren and her journal, “Estranged Labor, Habitus, and Verstehen in the Rise of Extreme Endurance Sports.” There has been an increase participation in extreme endurance events that Eren accounts to estranged labor. 
	After exploring causes and results of estranged labor you should think about how it specifically has and can affect you. Did a collective consciousness motivate you to go to college instead of a passion? Are companies using you as a free commodity to boost their advertising? Do you want participate in marathons to make up for lost physical movement? But most of all, what can you do to change it?

An Analysis on the Sexualization of Women in the Media
	Representation in the media matters. At a young age, children internalize messages from the pop culture they consume and perform imitations of the personalities they view as role models. This is extremely difficult for young girls who are often exposed to sexualized characters in the entertainment industry. As opposed to interesting and developed female protagonists, women are subjected to sexual and two-dimensional personalities, used to enhance the male gaze. The media aids in perpetuating concepts like the beauty myth by constantly portraying tall and thin women as the epitome of beauty, leaving those who do not fit the standard, without a voice. But why are women used solely for their bodies in these industries, as opposed to the intelligence and unique set of skills they offer? Short answer, sex sells. Under a patriarchal society in which males dominate these industries, women are objectified under the beauty myth and seen as a product to sell and make money from. 
	The media further objectifies women, by using the beauty myth as it’s template. Naomi Wolf describes the beauty myth as a political weapon that places women in a hierarchy based on their appearances, forcing them to fight each other for resources allocated by men. Essentially, men want beautiful women; women want to be beautiful. However, with the addition of the media, the standard of beautiful becomes impossible to obtain. Take for example, the Kardashians, these women are the face of pop culture, in commercials, hosting SNL, or the face of a designer brand, they dominate every social media platform. The Kardashian women have become the epitome of the sexy woman, with full lips, big breasts, tiny waists, and of course big butts. The problem with these depictions arises when these women promote their bodies as a natural outcome of exercising and dieting, and not from plastic surgery. This encourages the illusion that all women can and should look like this as, men find an hourglass body extremely attractive. When women do not fit this standard, they feel unworthy and excluded, despite their talents. The beauty myth allows the media to display one body type, which is just not attainable to average woman without developing an eating disorder or getting plastic surgery.
	Looking back on my experience with my first Wii game, I understand why I will never find a character I can identify with; I don’t fit the beauty myth and the game isn’t for my enjoyment. Like most video games, this game marketed towards men and men want beautiful women on their screens. The beauty myth provides the creators with the categories of the sexy Zero Suit Samus or the sweet Princess Peach character, while the belief that women are a “second sex” justifies this objectification. Unlike the men in the game, Samus is given unrealistic body standards which goes on to show how dethatched and disillusioned these creators are to the average female body. Looking at this puzzle through the lens of the beauty myth and women as a “second sex,” highlights the way this sexualization is justified and created to reinforce gender norms, leaving those who do not fit this tiny waist, tall, big breasted category, without a platform to express themselves. My feelings of unease towards the game were really feelings of exclusion that my brothers could not understand, as they chose characters that personified their proudest traits.  
	Representation contributes greatly to youth development by allowing children to visualize themselves as role models. Marvel movies like Black Panther and Shang Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings allow Black and Chinese kids to feel like superhero’s, however, these movies are still relatively new, showing Hollywood is just now starting to break barriers. As long as the entertainment industry is dominated by men, it will be marketed towards men who desire beautiful women on their screens. In the video game industry, which is extremely male dominated, even games that are targeted towards a young audience like Super Smash Bros. Brawl, will feature sexualized depictions of women to sell more games. With the view of women as a “second sex,” women’s bodies are objectified into products that can be sold for profit. The beauty myth just makes things easier for creators by providing them with the mold for the perfect money-making product. Young women deserve representation in the media that depicts an average body type, and showcases women for their intelligence and unique set of skills, as opposed to the two-dimensional eye-candy that is consistently displayed in pop culture.

Social Media Effects on the Beauty Standard in Women
Over the years, social media has grown into a platform that people tend to portray themselves on. However, when filters and photoshopping come into play, women begin to create a new beauty standard that is unrealistic. While social media platforms such as Instagram are increasing their body positivity posts, some are still not ending with positive effects. These negative effects lead women to have unrealistic beauty standards as well as trying to change themselves physically. Leading to the question what effects does social media have on the beauty standard in women? The effects of social media on the beauty standard in women include but are not limited to the formation of eating disorders, cosmetic surgeries, and strict fitness and diet goals. However, there are limitations on this subject because social media does not result in only negative effects. In recent years, social media has had an increase in positive posts in regard to body positivity, embracing one’s experiences and doing what makes them happy instead of what makes others happy. Depending on the mentality of the woman and the environment they are in can change how they are affected by beauty standards in social media negatively or positively. 
While Afful and Lazuka as well as their colleagues argue that social media has a large impact on women and beauty standards, Susruthi Rajanala, Mayra B. C. Maymone, and Neelam A. Vashi argue that the society one lives in and participates in has a higher impact. Maymone et al points out that when people find themselves more attractive, they are happier and have a better well-being. (Maymone et al. p. 1). This causes people to go about cosmetic surgeries to enhance themselves. Today’s beauty standards are also linked to wealth and how well someone is doing in their life. Therefore, people tend to have these cosmetic surgeries to please others if not for themselves.  Maymone et al. Some women undergo cosmetic surgeries to appear more professional looking in their workforce (Maymone et al. p. 2). The reasons for women undergoing cosmetic surgeries are very dependent on the environment they are surrounded by. If they believe that they do not look the part, they would appear more likely to have a surgery performed to help them in that aspect. If they feel that they look more professional, they may perform their job more effectively if they feel good while doing it. While this is not always the case, in my own experience I have felt more confident and done a better job at whatever I was doing if I felt that I looked better. It is important to notice the environment that a woman is in and whether that will affect the need to look a specific way. If the environment suggests that perfecting one’s appearance through weight loss, dieting, or cosmetic surgery is positive, then the women in that environment are going to feel pushed towards that decision. However, if the environment looks positively at being healthy, and not pushing people towards the contrasting culture, the women in that environment would not feel as pressured to make those changes. The examples and studies viewed by Maymone et al. Support the argument that social media as well as the environment can pressure women to surgically change their appearance to fit the beauty standards on social media. 
While this is not part of a source, the importance of real-life examples in my own life supports the argument as well that social media has an effect on beauty standards in women. Some may decide to take part in receiving the surgery while others will continue to pursue a healthy but not toxic lifestyle. They may get back to the body they had before, or they will not. Celebrities are slowly making it known that they do not have to portray themselves as perfect and flawless on social media. I personally believe that they are realizing that it is better to show their “human” side in order to abolish the unrealistic beauty standards that are shown on social media. In my own experiences, I have caught myself comparing my life in how interesting it is to my peers or celebrities and influencers as well as comparing how I look in comparison. It makes you think that if you can just figure out what their trick is to look a certain way then you will be happy. However, that is not the trick to being happy. I think people are also realizing that and doing what makes them happy regardless of how others are living their lives or how they look. Celebrities and influential people are also posting more about doing what makes you happy and not what makes other people happy. This is important because it contradicts the argument about social media having negative results on women. More recently there have been an increased number of body positivity posts that do not include pressure to live a specific life style and to embrace what makes you happy. 
In conclusion, my argument was supported by my sources as well as showing the possible limitations in the studies that I used. Social media does cause the formation of eating disorders, the want for cosmetic surgery, and negative fitness and diet culture in women. While it was shown that social media had a large part in these effects, it was also observed that the environment one lives in can play a part in beauty standards as well. Celebrities and influential people on social media are normally the people showing unrealistic beauty standards for the average person because of the edited and photoshopped pictures. This is normal for celebrities to do because they have professional pictures taken constantly. However, more recently celebrities have been opening up with their own experiences with eating disorders, beauty standards, and how they are expected to portray themselves. Since they are doing this, they have also started posting more on social media about body positivity especially after having a baby, and unfiltered photos in their posts. I think that celebrities and influential people that we look up to making this change in social media and beauty standards will be better for women and they will appreciate their bodies more instead of wanting to change it in order to cater to other people’s expectations.  The Beauty Myth: its history, and its contemporary effects

There is no doubt that men and women are different. Thanks to the continuous feminism waves that have taken place in different periods, women have been able to slowly crack the collective consciousness of patriarchy and sexism. The right to vote, the right to own land, equal educational opportunities, and many more rights have made the gender discrimination gap smaller and smaller. But why are eating disorders still more prevalent in women than men? Why does America spend more than  20 billion dollars every year on beauty products (Wolf 1991)? Why is there still a pay gap between men and women? Why do most employees prefer to have a male boss rather than a female one? Of all the barriers that women have been able to tear down, there is one restriction that still controls women and stops them from being truly free: The Beauty Myth. As of today, unrealistic beauty standards keep women in a constant fight with their identities, therefore not able to concentrate in achieving their personal and professional goals. Mass media plays an important role in the creation and distribution of the idols that girls and women aspire to look like.  
On module three from our Sociology class, we discussed the differences between sex and gender. We analyzed the collective consciousness that surrounds men and women and how society expects them to behave. We talked about how men are expected to be the head of the household, support a family, be  physically strong, hide their emotions, and show leadership and security. We also learned how women are expected to give birth, raise children, and be silent and prudent. It is normal for women to cry or be emotional, because women are expected to be weak. But even after all the feminist revolutions, why are women still not viewed equally among men? The Beauty Myth is what still keeps women restrained from achieving their full potential. Our society is still immersed in a collective consciousness that evaluates women based on appearances rather than knowledge or experience.
From the beginning of human civilization, physical differences determined what kind of tasks men and women should perform. Men would use their strength and stamina to do hard labor such as farming, hunting, and constructing. On the other hand, women were valued based on fertility and their ability to raise kids. It was like this for centuries; fertility was considered women’s main asset, and a fat, full woman was actually considered a sign of good health. It wasn't until the 16th century, around the time that the printing press was invented, that the proliferation of media began spreading all kinds of ideas across Europe and America. By the 19th century, the press had already spread the idea of how the perfect woman should look. In an effort to look more attractive, women began to put themselves through painful diets and uncomfortable corsets that would create a skinny waist and voluptuous hips and breasts. For decades, women were seen as second class humans. In medieval Europe, a woman's goal was to get married and fully depend on her husband’s income. Women were hardly judged by their appearance and only gained value by their husbands.
As years passed by, the Beauty Myth kept growing as the printing media began spreading faster. Then the Miss America pageant emerged. As the world began to praise and admire these models, girls and women began to think about the desirable body a woman should have. Having a perfect body became synonymous with compliments, success, and freedom. However, having the perfect model body was only achievable by extreme diets and exercise that marked the beginning of eating disorders. Going through the 20th century, the spread of mass media allowed the diffusion of the perfect female body. Magazines, television, and advertisements began to only show perfect models that represented the American beauty standards. Those who did not meet those standards would work as hard as they could to achieve the dream body.
Nowadays, the media continues to be a great influence on girls and young women. If we look closely at the way women are portrayed in the media, we can see a pattern on how these women are presented. Perfect hair, highlighting makeup, hourglass bodies, and high skirts is what women in the media look like. This is especially true on sport shows and events. The clothing these women would be wearing is most of the time extremely revealing and highlights their body’s curves. The sexualization of the body is part of the Objectification Theory (Roberts & Gettman, 2004) that goes hand in hand with the Beauty Myth because it creates a disconnection between mind and body that makes women more conscious about their bodies.
According to the self-objectification theory, when women create this third perspective of themselves, it makes them more self conscious which allows feelings of shame and anxiety to overpower. Women would continuously compare themselves with beautiful models which, in return, lead to feelings of discomfort and mortification. This eventually would stop them from participating in activities like going out, wearing a swimsuit, or even going to school and work. A study made by Fredrickson and colleagues (1998, as cited in Roberts & Gettman, 2004) and Gapinski, Brownell, and LaFrance (2003 as cited in Roberts & Gettman, 2004) consisted in examining men and womens’ reactions to their bodies in a swimsuit and a sweater. The results showed that women had a higher level of body shame compared to men while wearing a swimsuit. This traces back to the stereotypes present in the media. Girls grow up with images of what the perfect woman looks like, and a swimsuit that highlights perfectly seen areas can  trigger self-consciousness and lead to poor mental and emotional health.
The ironic part about the Beauty Myth and the self-objectification theory is that almost every “perfect” woman portrayed in the media is a product of computer alteration. Legs are stretched out, skin is highlighted or darkened, and even some models are digitally created by the morphing of several models. It is ironic because all these magazines talk about how to get the perfect body by natural processes while the models depicted as “real” are not even authentic (Consalvo, 1997, as cited in Roberts & Gettman, 2004)
Women who set up goals to unrealistic standards are hardly ever going to meet this desire. According to research, only a minority of women in the US are actually overweight, however, the majority of women claim to feel overweight (Crandall, 1994, as cited in Roberts & Gettman, 2004). Women pursuing an unrealistic dream creates this ongoing cycle of anxiety and frustration that can stop them from doing what they really want. These feelings of worthlessness and low self esteem, according to the Beauty Myth, have been set up by the patriarchy to convince women they do not deserve more. This explains why in the 21th century, where everybody has equal access to education and connections, there is still a pay gap between men and women.
According to a study made in Poland, there are a couple of theories that could explain the pay gap in this country. From prejudice taste by employers and clients, to the assignment of roles based on gender. The study collected, analyzed, and compared women and men’s wages from 1991 to 2015. During this time period, researchers made sure to consider education level, job experience, and wage level when comparing gross and net income. This study not only found out that there is a considerably big pay gap between men and women, but it also found that this pay gap tended to be greater in higher levels of employment. But how can citizens from a first world country in the 21st century still allow this phenomenon to happen? The research concludes that is mainly because it is socially accepted. The population in Poland still follows the Christian-catholic, which considers family as their highest value. Therefore, men are privileged over women with higher pay rates because they are still considered the main providers of the family. Women have accepted this secondary role because it is part of the collective consciousness of Poland’s society (Calogero, Borought, & Thompson, 2007).
All of these articles and researches show how deep the Beauty Myth is in our collective consciousness. Women have been taught that their body image is their ticket to a life of acceptance, success, love, and money. But when the market saw the opportunity to profit from girls and women’s insecurity, the mass proliferation of the “perfect” and “natural” woman created an unrealistic goal that continues to feed itself and grow from womens’ anxiety. The mass expansion of the perfect model has created unreachable expectations by the rest of society that now young women feel they need to reach. This has led to feelings of insecurity and incompetence that can affect the way women are seen because it sets very high standards. The self devaluation of women has allowed them to accept lower wages.
The Beauty Myth is the last, but the strongest barrier that women need to tear down in order to be truly confident and free. Feminism is women’s strongest ally, but there are still a lot of prejudices surrounding feminism for women. Women will finally gain power once society and themselves accept that femininity and beauty does not equal competency and civility. The Beauty Myth portraits women as beautiful and young, basically inert. But the modern woman is not inert, it is changing, progressing, and expressing their individuality (Wolf, 1991).
